




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Entrepreneurial Risk Taking, Inequality, and Public Policy: An Application of Inequality Decomposition Analysis to the General Equilibrium Effects of Progressive Taxation
Y1  - 1982/02/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261037
DO  - 10.1086/261037
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1
EP  - 21
VL  - 90
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The objective of this paper is to investigate the "conventional wisdom" that there is a policy conflict between the reduction of inequality and the encouragement of entrepreneurial risk taking. The paper attempts to provide a precise statement of this conflict in the context of the progressivity of tax regimes. Using the method of inequality decomposition analysis, a taxonomy is developed which locates the sources of the policy conflict in a precise fashion. A detailed analysis then shows that the conventional wisdom is misleading if not wrong, and that in many cases the claimed policy conflict is quite simply illusory.
AB  - The objective of this paper is to investigate the "conventional wisdom" that there is a policy conflict between the reduction of inequality and the encouragement of entrepreneurial risk taking. The paper attempts to provide a precise statement of this conflict in the context of the progressivity of tax regimes. Using the method of inequality decomposition analysis, a taxonomy is developed which locates the sources of the policy conflict in a precise fashion. A detailed analysis then shows that the conventional wisdom is misleading if not wrong, and that in many cases the claimed policy conflict is quite simply illusory.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261037
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261037
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Does Anticipated Monetary Policy Matter? An Econometric Investigation
AU  - Mishkin, Frederic S.
Y1  - 1982/02/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261038
DO  - 10.1086/261038
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 22
EP  - 51
VL  - 90
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A heated debate has arisen over the policy ineffectiveness proposition associate with the work of Lucas, Sargent, and Wallace. It postulates that anticipated aggregate demand policy will have no effect on business-cycle fluctuations, so that one deterministic, feedback policy rule is as good as any other from the point of view of stabilizing the economy. This paper develops a methodology for empirically analyzing rational-expectations models displaying this neutrality result and then applies it to the important question of whether anticipated monetary policy matters to the business cycle.
AB  - A heated debate has arisen over the policy ineffectiveness proposition associate with the work of Lucas, Sargent, and Wallace. It postulates that anticipated aggregate demand policy will have no effect on business-cycle fluctuations, so that one deterministic, feedback policy rule is as good as any other from the point of view of stabilizing the economy. This paper develops a methodology for empirically analyzing rational-expectations models displaying this neutrality result and then applies it to the important question of whether anticipated monetary policy matters to the business cycle.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261038
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261038
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Parental Preferences and Provision for Progeny
AU  - Behrman, Jere R.
AU  - Pollak, Robert A.
AU  - Taubman, Paul
Y1  - 1982/02/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261039
DO  - 10.1086/261039
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 52
EP  - 73
VL  - 90
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper develops a general preference model for analyzing parental allocations of resources among their progeny. The implications fro this model for the distribution of educational resources and earnings potentials among siblings are examined. A particular version of the preference model is estimated using data on the education and earnings of adult male twins. The estimates imply that parents care about offsprings' earnings inequality and provide more (less) resources to the less (more) able than is consistent with an investment model.
AB  - This paper develops a general preference model for analyzing parental allocations of resources among their progeny. The implications fro this model for the distribution of educational resources and earnings potentials among siblings are examined. A particular version of the preference model is estimated using data on the education and earnings of adult male twins. The estimates imply that parents care about offsprings' earnings inequality and provide more (less) resources to the less (more) able than is consistent with an investment model.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261039
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261039
Y2  - 2024/03/22
